  "prompt": "Do the first symphonies contain a \"Scerzo\" movement?",
  "response": "The first symphonies, particularly those from the Classical period (mid-18th to early 19th century), typically do **not** contain a \"Scherzo\" movement. Instead, they usually follow a four-movement structure that includes:\n\n1. **Allegro** (fast, sonata form)  \n2. **Andante or Adagio** (slow, lyrical)  \n3. **Minuet and Trio** (a dance-like movement in triple meter)  \n4. **Allegro or Presto** (fast, often lively)  \n\nThe **Scherzo** (Italian for \"joke\") as a symphonic movement was popularized by **Ludwig van Beethoven**, particularly in his later symphonies (e.g., Symphony No. 3 \"Eroica\" and onward). The Scherzo replaced the traditional Minuet and typically has a faster, more playful, and rhythmically driven character.\n\nBefore Beethoven, composers like **Joseph Haydn** and **Wolfgang Amadeus Mozart** adhered to the Minuet and Trio structure in their symphonies. Their symphonies generally do not include a Scherzo movement.\n\nSo, in summary: the earliest symphonies, especially those by Haydn and Mozart, do not contain a Scherzo. The inclusion of the Scherzo became more common in the Romantic era, particularly after Beethoven.",
